<br>
Actually…the RNG is very easy to “beat”. Each server (each is actually a network of many servers) has one box dedicated to cranking out the so-called random numbers.<br>
<br>
The way it works is, a sampler routine pulls whatever happens to be in the accumulator at any moment and thus has a “reasonably random” seed between .01 x 10^-31 and .1 x 10^-31. This value is then indexed by an extemely stable period (Sony uses the pulsar PSR B1509-58 for their indexing).<br>
<br>
An array of many seeds is generated over a period of time (let’s say 30 min), each precisely indexed. At the end of the 30 min, the values recorded over the cycle are analysed by a statistical package which finds and flags aberrant values (clumps of numbers which are too close in value).<br>
<br>
These flagged numbers are then compared to another array of values recorded on a central server for exactly the same time period. These other values are called P/PI’s (Probability/Psi Indicators). Back in the 1970’s, the casinos on LasVegas did a study to determine if there was any way that people’ desire to win at their casino games might in any way actually influence the supposedly random nature of the game. A six year study proved inconclusive because nobody saw that the data they were analysing was offset in a way which nobody imagined was possible.<br>
<br>
At some point someone figured out that the P/PI data being retrieved from test subjects matched up with startling accuracy IF one compared the current P/PI data not with the current games the test-subjects were playing, but with ones they would play later on! This time difference (roughly 1.75 hrs) is known as the Minden Offset. When factored in, it was found that something about the gambers…psycic?…mental? WAS affecting the randomness of the games, and thus indeed cutting into the house-odds.<br>
<br>
The finding were kept secret for years, and the casino-owners set up secret P/PI collection equipment in all of their casinos. They would constantly screen the data, and if “spike” in the data indicated that abnormally many people would soon be winning, they would find some excuse to close (usually for “maintenance”) until the spike blew-over.<br>
<br>
The NGC eventually got wind of this, and forced the casio-owners to stop the practice. Though the government has never lost interest in P/PI research, there really was no longer a market for its private use. Since EQ is not actual gambling however, it is legal for Sony to make use of the technology to help keep their RNG as perfect as possible. They use the P/PI numbers to filter aberrances (people overly focused on a certain mob popping, loot dropping, etc.) and generate a very clean, and truly random number.<br>
<br>
The trick is, now that you know what you know, simply decide to gamble about 1.75 hrs before you actually do, and concentrate on LOSING! That’s right!…just think about all those 2’s and 17‘s out of 1000 yer gonna’ roll! This will cause Sony’s RNG to be skewed toward higher numbers! (because it ~thinks~ you wanted the lower ones….). If you doubt this, just remember all the times you camped something and it never popped…when some guy who never heard of the mob walks by your camp 4 seconds after you leave only to trip over the mob you wanted!<br>
<br>
I have made over 150K so far with this system which works for farming too, but that process is way more complex to explain. It can work for you too!<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
-Morloc<br>
